                                >= Chapter II. =<

Audio Modules
█████████████

This chapter is the most extensive chapter in this documentation coz Audio
Modules are hard to explain and need a lot of explaining and description
to know all about them and to write a player.

Audio Modules are musicfiles, not streams like WAV & co, this means they are
not only saved audio data but they have also notedata in there. In principe
they work as everylike music keyboard where the different instruments are
saved as wavetable which means every instrument is sampled once with data
about it's frequency and how it can be looped.
Now in different channels there are now the notes which tell us how 'deep' eg.
how fast that instrument is to be played to sound like that note according to
it. There is some extra data like volume and extra effects like vibrato etc.
This channels are then mixed together and you get the resulting song.

Easy ey ? You can compare this to Midi with the only difference that this is
a software-only sollution. ;)
(This is not exact right cause nowadays there are soundcards for the PC which
do all the mixing work on hardware to free CPU power for other needs. For
example the GUS or the EWS 64XL are such types of soundcards and are used
very often in the demo scene.)

The origin of this type of music is the good old Amiga with it's MOD format,
which stands for 'MODule'. This was the normal way to produce music on the
Amiga coz it has a soundchip which do the mixing.
Of coz that type of music was much better and more realistic than that FM
synth sound on the PC like Adlib and so there appeared MOD player on the PC.
That MOD player was used in DEMOS first but the MOD format was too restrict
for the PC. It's limits belong to the harware limits of the soundchip of the
Amiga and so there appeared new formats like '8 channel' MODs, 669, MTM, S3M
and so on. The newest and most powerfull format is the IT (Impuls Tracker)
format. It is a mixing of the so long most used XM (eXtended Module) and the
older S3M (Screamtracker 3 Module) with some enhancements which makes it very
'realistic' to produce good music.

The descriptions of that formats are written during my implemetation into my
F/X player so there should hopeful no error exept typos or something.

First I will tell something about the origin of this format and it's tracker,
then I explain the build-up of that format and how it can be interpreted.
(Then I will explain the effect of every format which will take the most space
in here.)

MOD
▀▀▀

Aha, the Grandpa of all soundmodules :)

669
▀▀▀

This was the first module format on the PC which extended the MOD format

MTM
▀▀▀

Some more extended MOD

S3M
▀▀▀

The first format I implemented into my player coz it is relative easy but also
more powerfull then MOD. And of coz I like that format :)

The tracker which orginal generates S3Ms is the famouse 'Scream Tracker 3' by
the more legendary 'Future Crew'. As you can imagine is this the third
generation of their tracker but this one was a milestone in history.
It's format was more structured and allows (theoretical) up to 4GB of samples
as 8 or 16bit and mono or stereo. It can handle up to 32 channels
(in comparison to MOD a breakthrough) from which 16 can be digital and 16
FM synthese of the Soundblaster. But now there are also new S3Ms which use
all 32 channels for digital samples (espacially when saved with IT).
And another news was that the pattern (in which the notes and effect are
stored) are simply packed and reduce the space of them when saved to disk.


XM
▀▀

The complete break with the old MOD rules and a new beginning

IT
▀▀

Well, and this is the most genius format so long !



